<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sudan-Floods     08-21 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Floods,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Victims Still Isolated, Unaided</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Omar Abakr Idris removes his shoes before
wading through the knee-deep fetid water left behind by the worst
rains on record in this desert capital.
   Each step across what used to be a dusty dirt road unleashes an
overpowering stench. The vast expanse of water is contaminated with
excrement from overflowing pit latrines and from dogs, goats and
donkeys living in the village.
   Idris' village of Mayo, a shantytown of about 50,000 on
Khartoum's southeastern fringe, was among the areas hardest hit by
the deluge Aug. 4-5.
   ``We are struggling with life here now,'' said Idris, 48. ``We
are without water, without food, without homes, without transport,
without anything.''
   The storm dumped 8.4 inches of rain in 14 hours, six times the
amount that fell in all of 1987. For the past 30 years, annual
rainfall has not exceeded 4.3 inches.
   At least 58 people died, most as their mud huts collapsed on
them. Up to 1.5 million people _ more than a third of Khartoum's
nearly 4 million inhabitants _ were left homeless and more than
150,000 dwellings were destroyed, according to government figures.
   Most vulnerable were the people living in Mayo and 22 other
squatter camps around Khartoum. The illegal settlements hold
500,000 to 700,000 people who fled Sudan's southern civil war and
widespread drought. The vast camps of mud huts and burlap-covered
shacks are desperately poor and occupy the worst land.
   The Moslem-dominated government, at war with the Christian and
animist south, long has tried to discourage further settlement in
the squatter areas. It denies the areas any social services and
forbids the displaced people living there from digging wells.
   Official neglect threatened to leave most of the displaced
people beyond the reach of international relief after the storm.
The government initially refused aid but ultimately relented in the
face of the sheer magnitude of the disaster and the threat of
epidemics sweeping from the camps.
   Many relief workers still worry the unplanned areas will receive
less than their fair share of government aid.
   ``There will be a natural built-in bias towards planned areas,''
said Bryan Wannop, resident representative of the U.N. development
program which is helping coordinate non-government relief.
   Emergency aid has yet to reach most of those affected by the
flood, many of whom live in areas isolated by stagnant lakes which
have nowhere to drain.
   Nearly all the mud huts in Marzuk, an unplanned area of about
15,000 people in Omdurman across the Nile river from Khartoum, were
destroyed or damaged by the rains. The people said they needed
plastic sheeting and tents.
   ``They are very important because the children now are sleeping
outside,'' said Abdullahim Kody, a resident.
   ``Once I had two rooms,'' Kody said, pointing to a mound of
hardening mud. ``Unfortunately, they have fallen down.''
   Kody, Idris and others interviewed nearly two weeks after the
disaster said they received no help from anyone and were
desperately in need of food, shelter, and medicine.
   Health officials are predicitng deadly epidemics of water-borne
diseases as people cut off from drinking water supplies are forced
to drink from the pools left behind by the rainstorm.
   Thousands already have developed diarrhea. Malaria and typhoid
also are on the rise, and cholera is an imminent risk.
   Dr. Nicholas Ward, a world health organization expert on
diarrheal diseases an immunization, predicted 400,000 people,
mostly children, will get sick and at least 4,000 will die.
   Without treatment, as many as 40,000 will perish, Ward
estimated. But he said emergency health clinics established in
response to the disaster should forestall the worst.
   Diarrhea kills the young and the weak primarily through
dehydration and is treatable with a simple rehydrating mixture of
salt, sugar and water. But lack of fresh water supplies make even
this basic therapy difficult.
   Sudanese authorities blame insufficient supplies for delays in
granting relief. More than 2,000 tons of tents, blankets, medicine,
plastic sheeting, food and other items have poured into Sudan, but
officials have said it is about a tenth of what is needed.
   Disorganization and the dilapidated infrastructure of this North
African nation of 23 million also have hampererd the relief
operation.
   The rains knocked out telephones, disrupting coordination
between the army-run operation and non-governmental agencies. The
downpour also created mud bogs of roads already strewn with
potholes from years of neglect.
   Another threat comes from the swollen Nile river, which already
has swamped some island villages and is brimming near street level
in the capital. Officials are not sure when or whether the river
might overflow into the city.
   A pair of British cartographers working with government
surveyors has begun work on a contour map which will help determine
how much higher the Nile would have to rise before spilling into
Khartoum's streets.
   In the meantime, relief efforts will continue. And people like
Osman Geragandi Koko, who lives in a settlement built on a garbage
pile in north Khartoum, will do what they must to find food and
shelter.
   ``Previously there was drought and we got through that,'' he
said. ``We hope to get through this too.''
</TEXT>
