<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gulf-Analysis     08-21 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Analysis,0886</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran And Iraq Count Cost Of Eight-Year War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the smoke clears in the Persian Gulf
war with a U.N.-sponsored truce, Iran and Iraq are counting the
cost of a conflict that killed an estimated 1 million people but
ended with no victor.
   Peace talks scheduled to start Thursday in Geneva are likely to
be long and tough. Iran and Iraq are ancient enemies, and eight
years of war have only deepened old hatreds.
   Both countries, bled by the war, face mammoth tasks in
rebuilding their economies despite the oil wealth they used to
bankroll their military machines.
   Iran also faces the prospect of political turmoil as hardliners
such as Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, a vociferous critic
of ``defeatist'' diplomatic efforts to end the war; and more
pragmatic leaders, particularly Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani, battle for supremacy.
   Rafsanjani, considered the most powerful figure in Iran after
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, is widely seen as the man who
engineered Tehran's unconditional acceptance of the U.N. cease-fire
resolution last month when he realized Iran's military machine was
weakening after a string of battlefield defeats this year.
   Khomeini endorsed Rafsanjani's decision, widely seen as the
speaker's biggest political gamble, although the ailing patriarch
stressed that for him, ending the war was ``worse than drinking
poison.''
   So far, no senior Iranian leader has publicly challenged that
decision, which most Iranians have welcomed after eight years of
appalling human loss.
   But Rafsanjani, who also has made clear he seeks to end Iran's
isolation, faces an increasingly strong array of radicals led by
Mohtashemi and the prosecutor-general, Mohammad Khoeinihia, leader
of the militants who seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in November
1979, who oppose his pragmatist policies.
   They consider his efforts to end a war he clearly believed Iran
could never win flies in the face of the revolution's aim of
spreading Islamic fundamentalism.
   Analysts say the internal struggle for supremacy after Khomeini,
which has been swelling over the last two years as the patriarch's
health deteriorated, has only been intensified by Tehran's
acceptance of the cease-fire.
   On the ground, the two belligerents wound up virtually where
they started in September 1980, when Iraq invaded Iran, the map
unchanged after one of the longest conventional wars this century.
   Iraq's President Saddam Hussein, whose 1980 invasion is seen by
military analysts a major blunder, has emerged at least for now
more solidly entrenched in power in Baghdad.
   Iraq, which spent as much as $10 billion a year on its war
effort, is as much as $85 billion in debt, according to Western
economists. That makes it one of the world's biggest debtor nations.
   The war cost Iran an estimated $400 billion. Although it still
has about $5 billion in foreign reserves, its economy is in
tatters, its industry, particularly its oil installations, pounded
by Iraq's powerful air force.
   Khomeini, whose hatred of Hussein turned the war into a bloody
vendetta, remains the unchallenged authority in Iran.
   But his surprise decision last month to accept the cease-fire,
despite his exhortations to ``fight to the last drop of blood'' to
topple the Iraqi leader, has dented the 88-year-old religious
patriarch's credibility.
   The Iraqis, armed with superior weaponry and technology, won
something simply by surviving Iran's human-wave offensives and
wearing down the numerically superior Iranians, although Iraq used
outlawed chemical weapons and hammered Iranian cities with bombers
and missiles.
   Iran, virtually friendless and starved of the arsenal of
high-tech weaponry the Iraqis employed, can claim that it repelled
the invaders and fought them to a standstill.
   The war undoubtedly helped cement Khomeini's 1979 Islamic
revolution. Opponents of the cleric-dominated Tehran regime charge
that the fundamentalists deliberately perpetuated the conflict to
consolidate the infant republic and Khomeini's stern brand of Islam.
   With an end to the war now a possibility, the Arab countries of
the oil-rich gulf who were caught in the crossfire, and the rest of
the Moslem world, are heaving a collective sigh of relief.
   But an end to the war will have strategic repercussions far
beyond the gulf.
   Israel fears that Iraq, which has participated to some extent in
every Arab-Israeli war over the last four decades, eventually will
turn its combat-hardened military machine again on the Jewish state.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said last month that although he
did not see any danger of an imminent Iraqi attack, the military
buildup by Arab states spawned by the gulf war could be used
against Israel.
   With the gulf war out of the way, the Arab states are expected
to refocus their attention on efforts to solve the older
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   If Rafsanjani and his supporters, such as Foreign Minister Ali
Akbar Velayati, succeed in out-maneuvering their hard-line
opponents in Tehran, Iran's relations with the West are likely to
improve.
   That, in turn, has raised hopes that Iran can be persuaded to
use its influence with pro-Iranian Shiite extremists in Lebanon to
free foreign hostages, including nine Americans.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ed Blanche, based in Nicosia, is The Associated
Press' Middle East news editor.
</TEXT>
