<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 0102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuardWaitingList     08-21 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guard Waiting List,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Guard Says No Proof Of Waiting List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No evidence existed of a waiting list to get
into the Indiana National Guard headquarters unit Sen. Dan Quayle
joined in May 1969, Guard officials said Saturday.
   ``The existence or non-existence of any `waiting list' as to HHD
(Quayle's unit) cannot be verified due to the fact that no such
list can be found. Units were not required to maintain such lists
if they were under-strength and personal memories do not recall
such a list,'' two former top officers said in a statement released
Saturday.
   The statement was from John N. Owens, former adjutant general of
Indiana, and Robert G. Moorhead, former commander of the 38th
Infantry Division.
   Since Quayle was nominated as the Republican vice presidential
candidate, questions have been raised as to whether he used family
influence to gain entrance to the Guard.
   Owens and Moorhead point out that records show the headquarters
unit Quayle joined had vacanies the month before, the month of and
the month after the senator's enlistment.
   Quayle's unit had an authorized strength of 138 soldiers but had
134 people in April, 132 in May and 133 in June, Brig. Gen. James
Barney, deputy commander of the Indiana State Area Command, said at
a news conference Saturday.
   Neither Owens nor Moorhead could recall any inquiries on behalf
of Quayle.
</TEXT>
