<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes In West Beirut; At Least 15 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES casualties, corrects name of district where bombing
occurred, no pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded next to a Syrian army
checkpoint in Moslem west Beirut on Sunday morning, wounding at
least 15 people, police said.
   Police said a Syrian soldier at the checkpoint was among the
casualties. Most of the other wounded were Lebanese civilians,
including women and children.
   A cream-colored Mercedes packed with 88 pounds of TNT blew up at
8:40 a.m. (1:40 a.m. EDT), only two yards from the checkpoint
opposite a restaurant in the seaside Raouche district, police
reported.
   At least eight cars parked nearby were destroyed.
   Police said the car had been parked Saturday evening near the
restaurant which perches atop a cliff overlooking the
Mediterranean. They could not determine who owned the Mercedes.
   Syrian troops, armed with rocket-propelled grenades and
automatic rifles, sealed off the blast scene.
   Red Cross ambulances evacuated the casualties as the Syrians
fired in the air to make way for them.
   A police officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said most
of the wounded were passers-by. He said none of the restaurant's
staff or customers was hurt.
   The corniche where the bomb exploded is popular with Sunday
morning strollers.
   Twisted metal and glass shards from a nearby six-story apartment
building, the Mayfair casino, and another restaurant were strewn
for 150 yards around the scene of the explosion.
   ``I heard a powerful explosion that hurled me several meters.
Pieces of glass rained on me,'' said a 28-year-old casino employee
who declined to be named.
   The car bombing was the eleventh in Lebanon this year. The last
car bomb blew up in west Beirut's Cola district July 22, killing
seven people and wounding 48.
   More than 130,000 people have been killed in Lebanon's
13-year-old civil war between Moslems and Christians.
