<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     08-21 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Wounds 18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mercedes packed with explosives blew up
Sunday near a Syrian army checkpoint in Moslem west Beirut,
wounding 18 people and damaging cars and buildings, police said.
   No group immediately claimed of responsibility for the bombing
in the seaside Raouche district, which came during a confrontation
between pro-Syrian forces and hard-line pro-Israel Christians over
the election of a new president.
   The cream-colored Mercedes, packed with an estimated 88 pounds
of TNT, detonated at 8:40 a.m. only six feet from the checkpoint
opposite a fish restaurant, police said. It was not known whether
the bomb was detonated by remote control or a timing device.
   Police said three Syrian soldiers at the sandbagged checkpoint
were among the casualties. Most of the other wounded were Lebanese
civilians, including women and children.
   At least eight cars parked nearby were destroyed. The
restaurant's glass front was blown in and windows in several
neighboring buildings were shattered.
   Hours later, police said another car rigged with two rockets was
safely defused in south Beirut's seaside Ouzai district.
   The car was parked in front of a bakery about 50 yards from a
Syrian checkpoint. Police said the 107mm rockets were equipped with
a timing device but did not say when they were set to go off.
   Police said the Merecedes that exploded was parked Saturday
evening near the restaurant, atop a cliff overlooking the
Mediterranean on a winding hilltop road popular with morning
strollers.
   Several unexploded hand grenades and a mortar shell were found
in the wreckage of the car, police said.
   ``Had they exploded, it would have been a real disaster,'' said
a police officer at the scene who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Nervous Syrian troops armed with rocket-propelled grenades and
automatic rifles sealed off the blast scene, firing in the air to
make room for Red Cross ambulances rushing victims to hospitals.
   Glass shards from the Mayfair Casino and a string of oceanside
fish restaurants littered a radius of 150 yards around the blast
scene.
   ``I heard a powerful explosion that hurled me several meters.
Pieces of glass rained on me,'' said a 28-year-old casino employee
who declined to be named.
   The car bombing was the 11th in Lebanon this year. By police
count, 103 people have been killed and 353 wounded in the 10
previous car bombings.
   The attacks have been a byproduct of Lebanon's 13-year-old civil
war between Moslems and Christians, which has claimed more than
130,000 lives since it broke out in 1975.
   Fears of of a new outbreak of violence have been fueled by a
presidential election deadlock that threatens to create a power
vacuum after President Amin Gemayel's six-year term in office
expires Sept. 23.
   Christian hardliners backed by the Lebanese Forces, the nation's
main civil war militia, prevented the election of Syrian-backed
warlord Suleiman Franjieh Thursday by boycotting the election
session in parliament, blocking a quorum for a vote.
</TEXT>
