<DOCNO> AP880821-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ThirdWorldRoads     08-21 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Third World Roads,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Needs $90 Billion for Roads, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third World countries need $43 billion worth
of repairs to their roads, including many of their key
thoroughfares, because over the last decade they failed to spend
$12 billion or less to maintain them, the World Bank says in a
report.
   The largest sum _ $11 billion _ is needed in Latin America and
the Caribbean, followed by $9.3 billion in East Asia and the
Pacific, and another $9.3 billion in the poorer countries of the
Middle East, North Africa and Europe.
   The bank's experts said they were talking about a third of all
paved roads outside of towns and a quarter of the unpaved roads in
85 countries. They found that 40 percent of the paved roads will
need repair in the next 10 years, at a cost of another $40 billion.
   In 1984, the most recent year for which the report gives
figures, the countries concerned put out $6.5 billion for repair
and maintenance.
   ``But if these countries do not improve the management of roads,
the eventual cost of restoration could easily increase two- to
threefold, and the cost to users could rise even more,'' the report
warned.
   The World Bank, owned by 151 countries, is the biggest single
source of loans to help poor countries raise their living
standards. It has lent about $15.5 billion for roads since it was
founded at the end of World War II.
   Routine maintenance can cost as little as $480 a mile, while
rebuilding can cost more than $480,000 a mile, the report said.
   The experts found the hard core of the problem in southern
Africa. They took 61 Third World countries all over the world and
found that 16 of them had budgets too small to pay for the roads
they need. Of those 16, there were 11 where citizens' incomes have
been declining. Nine of the 11 are south of the Sahara.
   They found a different problem in China, India, Pakistan,
Bangladesh and Burma. Many of their roads were built long ago in
ways that do not suit today's traffic, and should simply be
replaced, the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
