<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TownBands     08-21 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Town Bands,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hills Are Alive Again with Sounds of Polkas, Waltzes, Military
Marches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hills of Massachusetts are alive
again with the sounds of polkas, waltzes and military marches as
town bands make a comeback in once-abandoned band shells and
gazebos.
   Retired musicians, teen-agers and middle-age mothers who haven't
played an instrument since high school are jumping on the bandwagon.
   ``You have no idea how much fun it is,'' said Roger Voisin, a
former first trumpet of the Boston Symphony Orchestra and a
third-generation town band musician. His grandfather conducted the
municipal band in the French city of Angers.
   The legacy continues. Voisin's 15-year-old granddaughter,
Jennifer Roy, sits behind him in the Great Barrington band shell
that was built last year to replace the 1904 bandstand that had
disappeared from its spot in front of Town Hall in the 1940s.
   ``Every once in a while I'll do a solo or a particularily
difficult piece and I'll feel a little pat on my back, as if to
say, `Good job, Grandpa,''' he said.
   Band shells sprung up in parks across the United States in the
1800s, but fell victim to radio, movie theaters and television sets
in the middle of this century. Several band shells were destroyed;
others simply were abandoned.
   One of the few towns that managed to keep the tradition going
despite the lure of other pasttimes was Shelburne Falls, which
boasts the second-oldest continuously operating town band in the
nation. The band has played every summer since its founding in 1835.
   Its secretary, Shirley Donelson, believes the band may be the
oldest.
   The 30-member Shelburne Falls Military Band includes one player
with at least a half-century of service and three players with more
than 40 years in the group. Among the players are a farmer, a
retired fire chief, a college music professor and a few high school
students.
   The band even has uniforms, a luxury among most bands. The
40-member Montague Community Band provides shirts but asks that
musicians bring their own chairs.
   Mrs. Donelson, 54, said she took up the saxophone she had left
behind in high school and joined the band as soon as her children
grew up. ``I didn't have time when I was raising a family,'' she
said.
   Her husband, Walt, 55, has beat the bass drum for the group
every summer since 1952. A carpenter, he designed and built the
town band shell in 1970.
   ``I do it for the fun of it,'' he said. ``If I did it for the
money, I'd be done years ago.''
   Like all town bands, the Shelburne Falls band depends mostly on
the generosity of the board of selectmen to keep going, but it also
raises money by charging fees for marching in other communities.
   The 50-member Pulaski Brass Band in Webster celebrated its 99th
year on Aug. 14 by marching a few blocks from its headquarters, the
Polish American Citizens' Club, to St. Joseph's Church, where it
was started by five men.
   The band has missed only a few summers, during World War II,
since its beginning and has never had trouble recruiting, members
say.
   ``We have no dues and no auditions,'' Walter Motyka, a 37-year
veteran of the group, told The Worcester Telegram. ``We had a
fellow once who really had no musical ability, so we let him crash
the cymbals.''
</TEXT>
