<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Eliana-AIDS Bjt   08-21 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eliana-AIDS, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adoptive Mother: Disappointed Over `Glass Cage,' Will Continue
Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother who won a two-year fight to enroll
her 6-year-old AIDS-afflicted daughter in school finds her victory
bittersweet.
   ``This is the closest Eliana has been to a classroom. But I
can't send her to school to sit in a cage,'' Rosa Martinez said.
   The 36-year-old licensed practical nurse has struggled to give
her daughter, who weighed 10 pounds when she was adopted at about
11 months, a home and medical care. Now she's fighting for an
education for Eliana.
   Mrs. Martinez is appealing a ruling by U.S. District Judge
Elizabeth Kovachevich allowing Eliana to start school Aug. 29,
provided she remains behind a glass partition, isolated from other
children in the classroom.
   Her attorney expects it to become a landmark case.
   ``The issues in this case involve critically important national
policy,'' said Steve Hanlon, who is taking the case to the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta. ``It's going to have
long-lasting precedential effects.''
   Ms. Kovachevich ruled that Eliana, who is retarded, may attend
Manhattan Exceptional Center, a school for disabled children. But
the judge spelled out restrictions.
   In the classroom, Eliana must stay isolated inside a specially
built glass booth until she is toilet-trained and stops sucking her
fingers. Other children may play with her only if their parents
sign consent forms.
   The enclosure, located toward the back of the room, must be
8-by-10 feet with a large plexiglass window and sound system. It's
to have a toilet and desk. An aide would be assigned to Eliana full
time.
   Hillsborough County school officials fought attempts to admit
Eliana to the classroom. They feared she might transmit to others
the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus through bodily fluids.
   However, the judge wrote, no AIDS cases have been proved to have
been transmitted through exposure to urine, feces or saliva even
though the virus that causes the disease has been found in these
bodily secretions.
   AIDS, according to the federal Centers for Disease Control, is
spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from
pregnant women to their offspring.
   For the past year, a teacher has come to Eliana's home an hour a
day; school officials wanted to continue that method of instruction.
   But Mrs. Martinez and Hanlon insisted that Eliana needed to be
with other children.
   In her Aug. 8 ruling, Ms. Kovachevich said she was trying to
address the concerns of both sides.
   Even though Mrs. Martinez says she won't send Eliana to school
next week, school officials are building an $8,000 glass enclosure.
The plumbing is already finished.
   When Mrs. Martinez first heard the judge's ruling she started to
cry. ``I was angry and confused,'' she said in an interview last
week.
   ``I said to myself, `There's no way I'm going to do that, see
her behind a cage watching other children and wanting to get out
and play with them.' Then there was the confusion, the fear. I
thought is this the only way we're going to be able to do it?''
   Hanlon quoted pediatric and psychological experts as saying the
classroom restrictions would be harmful to Eliana and could put
even more stress on her weak immune system.
   Hillsborough school board member and former teacher Marion
Rodgers called the booth ``cruel.''
   ``If we did this in any other school setting for any other
reason, the courts would have us there for child abuse,'' she said.
   Mrs. Martinez adopted Eliana after she responded to a radio
appeal in Puerto Rico for a baby living at a hospital.
   Doctors believe that Eliana, born prematurely, was exposed to
AIDS when she had multiple transfusions as an infant.
   She has been on the AIDS-fighting drug AZT for the past year and
her mother says she has improved noticeably over the last several
months. The child's homebound teacher confirms that.
   ``She was deprived of family and we became that. She was
deprived of health and we gave her the best medical attention we
could,'' Mrs. Martinez says. ``Now, I don't want her deprived of an
education. She needs more than an hour a week to progress. And she
needs friends.''
</TEXT>
