<DOCNO> AP880821-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Apartheid     08-21 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Apartheid,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Seeks To Strengthen Residential Segregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The government plans to push ahead
with tough new measures that would strengthen residential
segregation, despite critics who say the proposals are ``straight
out of the darkest ages of apartheid.''
   Members of Parliament meet Monday in Cape Town to debate a bill
aimed at tightening enforcement of the Group Areas Act, which
segregates all neighborhoods by race.
   Black activists, white businessmen and even the pro-government
newspaper Beeld have condemned the measure, saying it entrenches
apartheid and would force the evictions of thousands of blacks
living peacefully, but illegally, in ``whites only'' areas.
   The proposed Group Areas Amendment Bill would make it easier to
confiscate property and to evict and prosecute people living in
areas not designated for their race group.
   ``It is a wicked, wicked, bill,'' said Robin Carlisle of the
anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party. ``It will drive decent
people out of their homes.''
   The bill calls for hiring inspectors to check for violations of
the law. The maximum fine for property owners who allow a person to
live outside his group area would increase from about $165 to
$4,100. The maximum prison sentence would be increased from two
years to five years.
   South Africa has a surplus of housing in white neighborhoods,
but a severe shortage in black areas. Thousands of non-whites have
been moving into white areas such as Hillbrow in Johannesburg and
Woodstock in Cape Town in recent years.
   The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old Group
Areas Act, angering conservative whites opposed to integrated
neighborhoods.
   The issue of segregated neighborhoods is one of the hottest
topics in the campaign for nationwide municipal elections Oct. 26,
and the bill is seen as an accommodation to right-wing whites.
   President P.W. Botha said last week he believes segregated
housing is favored by 80 percent of whites, 70 percent of Asians
and people of mixed race and a majority of blacks.
   ``It is rubbish to say 70 percent of our people would support
the (Group Areas) Act,'' said Allan Hendrickse, leader of the
mixed-race chamber of Parliament. ``Mr. Botha is this country's
most dangerous liability. It is about time he stepped down to make
way for a person of greater vision and perception.''
   Lawmakers also will address legislation that would allow
creation of the first legal multiracial neighborhoods. Botha would
have veto power over any plans to create such ``open area.''
   Other housing-related bills on the agenda seek to toughen
existing laws against black slum areas and squatter settlements.
   South Africa has as many as 7 million squatters among its 35
million population, according to some estimates.
   ``South Africa is confronted by ... bills straight out of the
darkest ages of apartheid,'' said the independent Sunday Times, the
country's largest Sunday newspaper.
   ``Authorities will be armed with powers to summarily evict
thousands, perhaps millions of people,'' the Sunday Times said in a
front-page editorial. ``Why must the legal process be distorted,
property seized, witch hunters licensed and countless people be
rendered homeless?''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880821-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrafficCourt     08-21 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Traffic Court,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Runs Kangaroo Court, Law Study Asserts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judges in New York's traffic court system are
pressured to maintain high conviction rates and to give police
officers special guidance to make successful cases, a newspaper
reported Sunday.
   The system, run by the state Department of Motor Vehicles,
operates ``in a fashion that is unfair, both in face and
appearance, to the average motorist,'' according to an 11-month
investigation conducted by the state Bar Association and obtained
by the Daily News.
   ``Cases are not necessarily decided on the facts, but rather on
a preconceived idea of how many should be guilty,'' said Matthew
Jason, the former state Court of Appeals judge who led the inquiry.
   Among the findings of the study were that administrative law
judges are pressed to be tough on motorists and to give police
officers preferential treatment.
   The deputy commissioner of the motor vehicles department, Edward
Sheridan, told the newspaper that the bar association report
``completely distorted the record.''
   ``Bits and pieces of information were put together and they
leaped to conclusions not supported by the record and not supported
by a fair and competent review of the system,'' he said.
   The bar association report said supervisors pressure judges to
set higher fines and increase convictions. In addition, DMV
officials track the percentage of guilty and innocent verdicts and
average fines, and judges are required to review their monthly
records with their bosses.
   The report also says judges are ``virtual advocates for the
police'' who routinely ask the officers leading questions to help
them make their cases.
</TEXT>
