<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Iran     08-21 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Iran,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Diplomat Sees Imprisoned Briton in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran permitted a British diplomat on Sunday to
visit a Briton imprisoned in Tehran for nearly two years without
trial, the Foreign Office said.
   Diplomat David Reddaway, who went to Iran Aug. 12 following a
thaw in relations between the two countries, found Nicholas Nicola
``in good health and reasonably cheerful,'' a Foreign Office
spokesman said.
   They met for 30 minutes, and the diplomat gave the prisoner some
``creature comforts,'' including cheese and pickles from London,
the spokesman said.
   Nicola, who Britain says was a tourist, was detained by the
Iranians in September 1986 for allegedly firing a gun near the
Pakistan border. Iranian authorities said he had infiltrated into
their country from Pakistan.
   He has not been charged, and the Iranians barred consular access
to him until Sunday.
   The Foreign Office spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Reddaway had also been given an indication that he
will be able to see Roger Cooper, a second Briton held without
trial by the Iranians.
   Cooper, a businessman who lived in Iran for more than 20 years,
was accused of spying in November 1985. Britain has complained that
Cooper was initially charged with overstaying his visa and that the
spying charge came later.
   He and Nicola are held at Tehran's maximum-security Evin Prison.
   Permission to see Nicola was given at a meeting with Iranian
Foreign Ministry representatives earlier Sunday.
   Reddaway was sent to Iran to examine the possibility of Britain
resuming a full-time diplomatic presence there.
   A recent, gradual easing of strain between the two countries has
also raised hopes for release of three Britons, including Anglican
Church envoy Terry Waite, who are believed held in Lebanon by
pro-Iranian extremists.
   Eighteen foreigners are believed held in Lebanon, including nine
Americans. The longest-held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
