<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-21 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain Floods Streets in Phoeniz, Ariz.; Hail Falls in
Minnesota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rainfall caused flooding Sunday in Phoenix, Ariz., and
across portions of the Florida Panhandle, while hail pelted
west-central Minnesota.
   A flash flood watch was posted over parts of western Arizona and
Southern California, where a flood Saturday roared through a canyon
in historic, gold-rush Calico Ghost Town and swamped about five
dozen cars.
   Rain showers and thunderstorms spread across South Dakota and
northern Nebraska, from the southern half of the Atlantic Coast
across the lower Mississippi Valley, from central New Mexico into
Southern California and in the San Francisco area.
   Rainfall during a six-hour period ended at 2 p.m. EDT included
almost 3 inches at Pensacola, Fla., more than 1} inches at Cape
Hatteras, N.C., more than 1{ inches at Biloxi, Miss., more than 1
inch at Jackson, Miss., and almost an inch at Vichy, Mo., and
Orlando and Jacksonville, Fla.
   In Minnesota, heavy rain and small hail fell at Fergus Falls and
near Battle Lake; 1-inch diameter hail fell at nearby Detroit Lakes.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Arcata and Crescent City, Calif., to 100 degrees at
Altus, Okla. The low temperature for the nation Sunday morning was
34 degrees at Butte, Mont.
   The national weather forecast for Monday called for showers and
thunderstorms from Florida and southern Georgia across southern
Mississippi and eastern Louisiana, from the upper and middle
Mississippi Valley across eastern portions of Kansas and Nebraska,
and from central Colorado to central Arizona.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 60s in eastern New
England, 70s from the rest of New England across Virginia and the
Great Lakes, and over the central and southern coast of California
and central Colorado and central Arizona. Temperatures were
forecast to reach 100 degrees or near 100 in southwest Oregon,
north-central Texas and Oklahoma, with nearly 105 in the desert
Southwest. High temperatures in the remainder of the nation should
be in the seasonable 80s and 90s.
</TEXT>
