<2ND_LINE>AM-Chavez Fast, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0685,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Labor Leader Ends Fast at Communion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with details on condition; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DELANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm labor leader Cesar Chavez ended his
36-day fast at a Mass Sunday by breaking bread with the children of
Robert Kennedy as thousands showed their support for his boycott of
California table grapes.
   ``Today I pass on the Fast for Life to hundreds of concerned men
and women throughout North America and the world who have offered
to share the suffering,'' Chavez said in a statement read by his
son Fernando Chavez.
   An emaciated Chavez, who according to his doctor lost 33{ pounds
or 19 percent of his body weight, was assisted to the Mass with his
arms draped around the necks of two other sons, Anthony and Paul
Chavez.
   Jesse Jackson attended with Kennedy's widow, Ethel, and both
appeared shocked at Chavez's condition. Also attending were three
of Mrs. Kennedy's children, Kerry, Rory and Christopher.
   The senator dramatically shared a Roman Catholic Communion that
ended Chavez's first major fast 20 years ago.
   Jackson began a three-day fast of his own to support the boycott
called to protest use of certain pesticides on table grapes.
   Thousands of union supporters, including movie stars and
politicians, attended the Mass held outdoors under a giant white
tent in near 100-degree heat.
   After he sat in a wooden rocker, Chavez leaned over to his
96-year-old mother, who was crying, and dabbed her eyes with a
handkerchief.
   Chavez, 61, kept up the water-only fast, his longest, despite
doctors' advice that he was endangering his health. He conducted a
25-day fast in 1968 and a 24-day fast in 1972.
   Since he began the fast July 17, the United Farm Workers union
president suffered from escalating bouts of nausea, vomiting,
dizziness and cramps.
   Doctors caring for Chavez were concerned last week that he
wouldn't have the strength to sustain the fast until Sunday. His
doctors worried about his early dehydration and elevated levels of
uric acid, which can lead to kidney failure.
   Doctors reported on Aug. 13 that Chavez had consumed all of his
body fat and that he was beginning to burn muscle tissue.
   After the Mass, Chavez was taken from the union compound in this
community 150 miles north of Los Angeles to an undisclosed location
where he will have a liquid diet, including light broth and
non-citrus juices for a week to 10 days, said one of his
physicians, Dr. Marion Moses.
   ``Recovery will be long and slow,'' she said, adding that
Chavez, a vegetarian, began the fast in good health and remained
mentally sharp throughout.
   The mass was Chavez's first public appearance since Aug. 11,
when he ceased attending nightly community meetings.
   Chavez began this fast to emphasize his demand for a ban on five
pesticides used on table grapes. The union claims the materials
cause cancer in field workers and pose other serious health risks.
   Grape growers and grocers blasted Chavez and the union for
unduly frightening consumers about the safety of table grapes in an
effort to fight a political battle.
   Chavez raised the pesticide issue in 1986, and called for
Captan, Dinoseb, Phosdrin, methyl bromide and Parathion to be taken
off the market.
   In the early days of this fast, Chavez held union meetings,
visited with union delegations, meditated, prayed and went on a
daily walk.
   As his strength waned, Chavez steadily scaled back his
activities. He spent increasing amounts of time bedridden in a
small bare room in the union's retirement village, and his staff
entered the room only at his request.
</TEXT>
