<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-21 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKENMUTH, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This town isn't quite sure whether
it's taking a licking or getting a compliment in a restaurant
chain's television ads tweaking its famous chicken dinners.
   The ads, scheduled for broadcast in Michigan and the Cleveland
area for Elias Brothers Restaurants, feature an older, white-haired
Southern gentleman not unlike Col. Harlan Sanders of Kentucky Fried
Chicken fame. He suggests customers buy their chicken at Elias Big
Boy restaurants instead of ``Frankenmuth _ wherever that is.''
   Talk chicken in this Saginaw County town and you're talking
Zehnder's of Frankenmuth and Bavarian Inn Inc., which jointly hold
the rights to the phrase ``Frankenmuth Chicken.''
   Officials with the two restaurants said they were routinely
checking whether the Elias Brothers ads represented trademark or
copyright infringement.
   ``We're not really upset about it,'' said Donald D. Keller,
marketing director for the Bavarian Inn. ``We're not trying to take
action against Big Boy or planning any kind of negative move at
this time, but we have a reputation that has taken many years and
millions of dollars to develop.
   ``There is another side of it, though,'' he added. ``We're
terribly flattered we've got that kind of reputation, that
comparing their chicken to ours is a way to show they know we are
the mark of excellence.''
   ``Frankenmuth is a very popular stop for chicken dinners,''
agreed Tony Michaels, marketing director for Warren-based Elias
Brothers. ``Big Boy is also popular for chicken. So we're really
using it as a means of comparison.''
   Michaels also stressed that the ads carry a disclaimer below the
Colonel Sanders look-alike reading, ``Not who you think it is.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sponsors of a food festival here ordered
up samplings of food from many of the city's restaurants and a
large chocolate milkshake. In fact, they claim it was the largest
shake on record.
   At 4 p.m. Saturday, a 40-foot dairy truck brought 1,500 gallons
of milkshake to the annual Taste New Haven.
   The giant shake was intended to top the 50-gallon record set in
1988 and the record of 250 gallons that will appear in 1989
editions of the Guinness Book of World Records.
   No one from the record book was present to certify the event,
but witnesses were on hand to provide sworn statements, said Patty
LaVigne, promotion director for Bridgeport radio station WEZN, a
Taste New Haven co-sponsor.
   The confection was donated by Baskin-Robbins Ice Cream to be
sold at $1 per 16-ounce serving, with the proceeds going to the
Muscular Dystrophy Association.
</TEXT>
