<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 2042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-LastEmperor     08-21 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Last Emperor,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Last Emperor' Opens to Sell-Out Crowds in Beijing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Last Emperor'' opened Sunday in the Chinese
capital to packed theaters but moviegoers gave a muted reaction to
the film about the end of China's pre-communist royal dynasty.
   One woman, waiting for a bus after the movie, said, ``The
beginning was good, very riveting, but the last part was too
serious.'' She also said the scenes of a communist re-education
camp were not realistic but did not elaborate. She declined to give
her name.
   The film about the life of China's last emperor, Henry Pu Yi,
will have its official Beijing premier Sept. 27. Italian director
Bernardo Bertolucci, the film's two producers and John Lone, who
played Pu Yi, will be invited to attend.
   Two Beijing theaters on Sunday began showing a 10-day special
run.
   The Chinese audiences, often noisy during movies, were usually
quiet.
   But scenes of zealous Red Guards marching alleged
counter-revolutionaries through the streets during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution drew chatter and laughter. Some viewers joined
in the singing and chanting.
   The 49-cent ticket price, three times the usual cost, did not
seem to affect sales for Sunday's showings. Most moviegoers who
were questioned said they came to see why the film won nine Oscars,
including the award for best picture, at the Academy Awards in
April.
   After the showing, ``Pretty good'' and ``OK'' were typical
comments.
   A few people said they went to see actress Joan Chen, who played
the empress. Chen is a Chinese actress who went to the United
States in 1981.
   One man complained that ``using a foreign actor to depict Pu Yi
was hardly fitting.''
   A college student praised the film as historically accurate and
said he wanted to see it a second time.
   ``The Last Emperor,'' which opened in the United States in
December, was to be released in Chinese theaters in June but that
date was postponed. The Film Bureau, which must approve all foreign
films shown in China, said the time was needed to dub the film into
Chinese.
   But there was speculation that officials might be unhappy with
the film's treatment of Communist Party history and that cuts were
being made. The bureau denied that.
   Li Zongyue, an editor for China Film Press who has seen both the
original movie and the Chinese version several times, said minor
cuts were made generally of scenes deemed unsuitable for children.
   Capital Theater Manager Sun Guangyin said the responses of
moviegoers were mixed.
   Some viewers said they wanted to see ``Last Emperor'' again, but
others said it wasn't nearly as good as a 30-part Chinese
television series on Pu Yi, also called ``The Last Emperor'' and
nationally broadcast earlier this year.
</TEXT>
