<DOCNO> AP880821-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PragueSpring 4thLd-Writethru   08-21 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prague Spring, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0704,0887</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousads March On Anniversary of 1968 Invasion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to move up reference to police response
and UPDATE with reports of tear gas, dogs used against some
demonstrators; picks up 14th graf pvs: Dvorak said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot squads broke up a protest
that began when 10,000 people marched through the capital Sunday to
mark the 20th anniversary of the Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed
the reforms of 1968.
   Baton-swinging police fired tear gas and charged the protesters
with dogs about two hours after a chanting, clapping crowd began
marching through the city. The march had dwindled to about 1,000
people when police moved in, beating at least two people and
dragging others away.
   Waving Czechoslovak flags, the crowd began a march in Wenceslas
Square after a rally where hundreds signed a petition calling for
democracy, human rights, the abolition of censorship and the
withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   Many chanted the name of Alexander Dubcek, who as Czechoslovak
Communist Party leader instituted the ``Prague Spring'' reforms
before Soviet-led troops invaded on Aug. 20-21, 1968.
   At least five people were detained at different sites Sunday,
including prominent activist Jan Urban. It was not known if Urban,
a member of a human rights group called Charter 77, was released.
   The crowd that left Wenceslas square was joined by thousands of
onlookers and the march swelled to about 10,000. Police made no
move to disperse the crowd until it had thinned and protesters
tried to return to the square.
   Police charged and dispersed the crowd, but no reports of
injuries were available. Reporters saw helmeted police beating at
least two people and two others were dragged away after shouting
``Dubcek'' and ``Freedom.''
   The official CTK news agency said in a brief dispatch that
``groups of people attempted disturbing actions'' in Wenceslas
Square.
   It was ``peaceful at the beginning. More prounounced attempts at
provocation were recorded ... after the crowd moved to the Old Town
Square and during a march through the streets of Prague,'' CTK
said. `The considerate and decisive action of the police prevented
riots.''
   In Moscow, an estimated 500 demonstrators gathered in a central
park. When they began chanting ``Prague, Prague,'' police charged
and dispersed the crowd. Several dozen people were taken away but
the number of arrests was not known.
   About 100 demonstrators staged a second rally along Moscow's
Arbat shopping mall, said Alexander Chuyev, a member of an
unsanctioned political party called the Democratic Union. He said
police arrested an unspecified number of protesters.
   Before the march in Prague, a group calling itself Independent
Peace Initiative earlier met in Wenceslas Square and drew up a
10-point petition. Peace campaigner Tomas Dvorak read it as
hundreds loudly applauded each point.
   Dvorak said the petition would be sent to Czechoslovak state,
government and party leaders and the state-run media.
   At one point, a policeman passed through the tightly packed
crowd and grabbed copies of the signed petitions. The crowd jeered
and yelled ``Shame.'' Reporters saw police spraying mace into the
face of at least one citizen.
   Earlier on Wenceslas Square, 200 people walked behind two
representatives of the Charter 77 movement, Eva Kanturkova and
Tomas Hradilek, who tried to lay flowers by the statue of King
Wenceslas.
   Uniformed police pushed back the two activists and others who
tried to lay flowers in memory of countrymen killed in street
violence after the invasion.
   Plainclothes men swiftly gathered up flowers thrown at the
monument as the crowd sang the Czech and Slovak national anthems
and applauded.
   Miss Kanturkova said she and Hradilek came to the square in
place of three group spokesmen detained Saturday as they walked to
the Soviet Embassy with an appeal to the Kremlin to tell the truth
about the 1968 invasion.
   A French reporter said one of the three, Bohumir Janat, told him
that he and group member Milos Hajek were released late Saturday
after a few hours in detention. An informed source said the third
man, Stanislav Devaty, was freed Sunday in his home town of
Gottwaldov.
   After the anthem singing, police detained at least two people
and a third wearing a Czechoslovak flag on his jacket was seized an
hour later.
   Outside a radio station, police checked the documents of eight
people who tried to lay flowers there and detained at least one.
   One man whose documents were checked, Vlastimil Kula, 37, said
he went to the square because ``it is the 20th anniversary of the
act the nation can't agree with.''
   When Aug. 21 dawned 20 years ago, this nation's 15.5 million
people woke up stunned to realize that their communist allies had
invaded to crush what official media call the danger of
counterrevolution and Czechoslovakia's withdrawal from the Warsaw
Pact.
   Prague's cautious communist leadership, installed to crush some
of the very innovations now favored in Moscow, recently embarked
upon carefully controlled economic reform and has allowed
independent groups and cultural activists more leeway.
   But Sunday's heavy police presence indicated the Prague
leadership will not tolerate renewed protests against the invasion.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass reiterated Friday that the
invasion was justified.
</TEXT>
