<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Protest     08-21 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Protest,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cape Town Workers Protest New Labor Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-SAfrica-Apartheid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 2,500
demonstrators held a peaceful rally Sunday inside Cape Town's City
Hall to protest labor laws scheduled to go into effect next month.
   The rally, attended mainly by black workers and union leaders,
was organized by the Congress of South African Trade Unions, the
nation's largest labor federation.
   It called the rally to oppose the Labor Relations Amendment Bill
that will take effect Sept. 1. Union leaders say the measure will
make it more difficult to have legal strikes and gives employers
greater legal powers to settle labor disputes.
   Some employer organizations also have expressed reservations
about the bill, saying it could lead to more labor-management
confrontations.
   Millions of black workers stayed away from their jobs for three
days in June when the bill was being considered by the
white-controlled government.
   Meanwhile, police said Sunday that five blacks were killed in
townships around the southeastern city of Pietermaritzburg.
   It said police fired on a group of blacks stoning a private
house in Hammersdale township and three men were killed.
   A man was killed in the same area by a group of blacks and a man
was stabbed to death in Mphumalanga township, according to the
brief police report. It gave no further details.
</TEXT>
