<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BakkerHouse     08-21 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bakker House,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Bought Jim and Tammy's Home Unhappy with Notoriety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGA CAY, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who bought the lakefront home of
former PTL television evangelist Jim Bakker is remodeling the
$685,000 house and is hopeful its notoriety will die down.
   ``It's just a house and it happens to be a little famous,''
Robert Rubino said of the 10,266-square-foot house.
   A lot of curious people still stroll down his driveway to look
at the house that once belonged to Bakker, who was forced from the
ministry in a sex and money scandal.
   Little evidence of the Bakkers' taste will be left once the
redecoration is complete, Rubino said.
   For example, the gold-plated swan bathroom fixtures and the
green carpet that covers most of the house will be removed, and a
19-by-22-foot closet will be changed into a bedroom.
   The four-bedroom, five-bathrom home has a 36-foot-long swimming
pool, a boat dock, a marble foyer, an exercise room and a music
room.
   Some of the furniture and appliances were included in the sale,
Rubino said, and he will keep most of the appliances, but the
Bakkers' furniture is just not his taste.
   ``I looked at the house and it was just what I wanted,'' he
said. ``I am going to make it into a very upbeat California look.''
</TEXT>
