<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Aquino     08-21 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Aquino,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says She Won't Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Sunday
she would not resign but would continue governing this factious
country because she had a covenant with the Filipino people and a
``contract with God.''
   Mrs. Aquino made no direct reference to the Aug. 13 demand by
Vice President Salvador Laurel that she step down and call new
presidential elections.
   But she told about 2,000 people at ceremonies marking the fifth
anniversary of the slaying of her husband, opposition leader
Benigno Aquino Jr., that forces bent on destabilizing the
Philippines were working against her.
   ``Every step we have taken toward progress has been challenged,
particularly at this time of the year, by those determined to see
this nation fail,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   ``But you and I shall not let it ...'' she added. ``For my
mandate is with this nation, not with its enemies. My covenant is
with the constitution, our contract is with God.''
   She added: ``For my mandate is with this nation, not with is
enemies. My covenant is with the constitution, our contract is with
God.''
   In a letter to the president, Laurel had accused her
administration of incompetence and of failing to stem the 19-year
Communist rebellion.
   Laurel offered to resign if Mrs. Aquino did, but added that if
she refused, he would remain vice president and join the
opposition. Mrs. Aquino has so far not responded to Laurel in
writing.
   Last week, Laurel met with opposition leaders to discuss forming
a unified opposition party. But his call for a new election has
failed to gain the support of major politicians.
   The next presidential election is set for May 1992.
   Laurel and opposition leaders have charged that the Aquino
administration is rife with corruption. They have compared it to
the final years in office of ousted President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino came to power after Marcos was toppled by a
civilian-military uprising on Feb. 25, 1986. The revolt culminated
a wave of public outrage sparked by the Aug. 21, 1983,
assassination of her husband.
   He was murdered while leaving a jet under military escort. He
had just flown home after three years self-imposed exile in the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
