Communist rebellion.
   Laurel offered to resign if Mrs. Aquino did, but added that if
she refused, he would remain vice president and join the
opposition. Mrs. Aquino has so far not responded to Laurel in
writing.
   Last week, Laurel met with opposition leaders to discuss forming
a unified opposition party. But his call for a new election has
failed to gain the support of major politicians.
   The next presidential election is set for May 1992.
   Laurel and opposition leaders have charged that the Aquino
administration is rife with corruption. They have compared it to
the final years in office of ousted President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino came to power after Marcos was toppled by a
civilian-military uprising on Feb. 25, 1986. The revolt culminated
a wave of public outrage sparked by the Aug. 21, 1983,
assassination of her husband.
   He was murdered while leaving a jet under military escort. He
had just flown home after three years self-imposed exile in the
United States.
</TEXT>
