<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SchererFight Bjt   08-21 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scherer Fight, Bjt,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capsule Capers: Scherer Family Fuss Likened to `Dynasty' Drama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tune in this week for the next episode in the
family feud over R.P. Scherer Corp.
   Stockholders have been pitted between the capsule maker's
largest shareholder, Karla Scherer Fink, and her estranged husband,
Scherer executive Peter Fink, in a proxy battle that peaked at the
company's annual meeting last Wednesday.
   ``I feel like over the last few weeks I've been watching nothing
more than a live episode of `Dynasty,' and frankly, I think it's
pathetic,'' said Arthur Hudson, a shareholder and former vice
president.
   Mrs. Fink, daughter of the company's late founder, was seeking
three board seats for her faction, whose mission is to sell the
company. Not surprisingly, management has touted the not-for-sale
position.
   Results of the vote are expected when the company reconvenes its
annual meeting at 10 a.m. EDT this Wednesday.
   Yet even if directors backing a sale are elected, analyst Dean
Gulis at the Detroit investment firm Roney & Co., said, ``You go
back to the basic, fundamental issue here'' _ and that is, he said,
does anyone want to buy the company.
   Scherer's stock is trading around $26 a share, sharply higher
than the $16-a-share selling price of a year ago. But analysts
attribute the increase to the boardroom pathos, which has put the
spotlight on the company.
   Lawrence Obstfeld, an analyst with Commonwealth Associates in
New York, said he doubted any purchase offer would approach the
$26-a-share level.
   ``I don't see how anybody could pay that much,'' he said.
   Analysts note that the biggest profits in the pharmaceutical
industry come from companies that produce new products; Scherer is
engaged only in packaging.
   ``I think it is a fine company in and of itself, but as a
possible acquisition for a drug company or chemical company, it
doesn't make sense,'' he said.
   Mrs. Fink, supported by her brother, John S. Scherer, thinks
this is an opportune time to sell the company because there is no
guarantee Scherer's recent record annual sales of $290.7 million
and earnings of $15.1 million will continue.
   ``John and I watched our father build this company. He made our
mother and their children partners in it nearly 50 years ago ...
and I believe he would have heartily endorsed a sale,'' she said.
Mrs. Fink and her brother control about 38 percent of the company.
   Peter Fink, Scherer's president and chief executives officer,
said there have been no offers and stressed that shareholders would
profit most if the company remained independent. He said he is
trying to prevent the dispute from becoming a distraction for
Scherer's 2,800 employees.
   ``I'd rather not refer to them as damage control measures,'' he
said after last week's stockholder meeting. ``We've tried to
contain the diversion to as few people as possible.''
   Some stockholders say the company will be damaged whatever the
outcome the family dispute, which saw Mrs. Fink file for divorce
weeks after the board rejected her sale proposal.
   ``What we are really witnessing here is the wounding of a unique
and special company,'' Hudson told about 200 people at last week's
meeting.
   Mrs. Fink says she just wants what is best for stockholders.
   Four months ago Mrs. Fink rejected a suggestion by some
directors that the company pay a one-time dividend that would
benefit her and her brother, in return for reducing their voting
power.
   ``I think that's the kind of deal I'd try to cut right now,''
Gulis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
