<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BorschtBelt 1stLd-Writethru   08-21 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Borscht Belt, 1st Ld-Writethru,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Borscht Belt Image Downplayed As Catskill Resorts Attempt
Revitalization</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Margo Jones ...' to include beet in recipe.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTICELLO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state's venerable Catskill
Mountain resorts, once known collectively as the ``borscht belt''
because of their ethnic flavor and abundance of food, are trying to
update their image.
   These days, some resorts are trying to be part of the ``sushi
belt.''
   Tourism officials distribute brochures in Japan praising the
region's golf courses. The tables at the golf clubhouse of the
Concord Hotel, the region's largest, have buffet menus printed in
both English and Japanese.
   It's just one indication of how times are changing for the
region, whose old ways were popularized in the romantic movie
``Dirty Dancing.''
   Margo Jones doesn't cringe at the mention of borscht, the beet
and cabbage soup popular at the predominantly Jewish hotels, but
Sullivan County's publicity director quickly steers the
conversation to a new nickname _ CatskilLand.
   The name, she said, is meant to convey the Catskills' more
active image as a center for sports and recreation.
   ``I don't think we'll ever get away from that ethnic image and I
don't think we want to,'' Jones said. ``Some of the things we like
about the image are the sense of tradition, a sense of family and a
warmth that you don't get from a chain hotel.''
   Milton Kutsher, for example, still prowls around the huge resort
in Monticello his family has run since 1907.
   Nevertheless, many of the 500 resorts that once dotted the area
have folded or converted to other uses; about a dozen giants now
handle the bulk of the visitors.
   Like many resort areas close to big cities, the Catskills _
about a two-hour ride from New York City _ began to fade as a
tourist destination in recent years. Air travel made other resorts,
both in the United States, the Caribbean and overseas _ more
accessible.
   The summertime routine of large meals broken up by an occasional
game of ``Simon Says'' was also less appealing to newer generations
of Catskills visitors. Even the hotels' nightclubs, which gave
birth to dozens of Hollywood careers, didn't seem so attractive
anymore.
   It was a case of adapt or die, and the Catskills did a better
job than areas like the Adirondack Mountains in upstate New York,
said Dan Lee, travel industry analyst for the investment firm
Drexel Burnham.
   ``To some extent, the times are changing back toward the
Catskills,'' Lee said. ``You have a rise in dual working couples.
That segment has money, but what they don't have is time. More
likely a two-career couple wants to take three days off and go
someplace nearby and relax and have a lot of activities there.''
   That's why ``CatskilLand's'' color brochure shows a young couple
whacking a tennis ball, dipping into a swimming pool and hitting a
golf ball. Skiiers and other weekend athletes are most welcome.
   Resort owners continue to use their imaginations to draw guests.
Grossinger's hosted the first ``singles only'' weekend back in
1962; a concept updated with an '80s twist at the Concord resort,
which publishes its own newsletter with personal advertisements.
   Hotels also have recently sponsored special weekends for single
parents and for infertile couples, Jones said.
   The Catskills' crowds also aren't as predictable as they used to
be. The families who still come to the Catskills for their bar
mitzvahs now room side by side with corporate executives on
retreats or training seminars, Kutsher said.
   At West Coast travel shows, Jones said she's known as ``the golf
lady'' among Japanese tourists who enjoy the relatively uncrowded
Catskills links.
   Many of the large hotels are also expanding their services to
include condominiums offered for use by time-sharing vacationers.
   While the Catskills can claim a revival _ Jones said her office
had 101,000 inquiries from tourists in 1986 compared to 24,000 in
1980 _ it can't say the comeback is complete.
   Brown's Hotel, one of the top resorts, filed for bankruptcy last
month, although the hotel remains open. Grossinger's, once the king
of the Catskills, has been closed since 1986, although its new
owners promise a remodeled resort will debut in 1989.
   ``It hurt us a lot individually because we were friends with
these people,'' Kutsher said of Grossinger's closing. ``But
Grossinger's will rise out of the ashes.''
   If it does, its new owners hope it will typify the new
Catskills. The newly named Grossinger's Resort and Spa will contain
some non-kosher restaurants and townhouses, said Bernie Roth, the
resort's general manager.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880821-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DropoutCampaign Bjt   08-21 0889</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dropout Campaign, Bjt,0921</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland Oil Will Be Anonymous Sponsor In Campaign Against Dropout
Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. HACKETT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. spends millions of
dollars to improve education in this country, but the company's
name will be missing from the latest attack on the high school
dropout problem.
   A series of 30-second television and radio spots and newspaper
and magazine ads will be released nationwide this week and be
identified as public-service announcements from two not-for-profit
organizations: the Council for State Governments in Lexington and
the Advertising Council in New York.
   Ashland donated materials and services for the ads but chose to
remove its name from them, remain anonymous and give credit to the
two not-for profit groups _ an action described as unique and
unprecedented by both councils and the National Dropout Prevention
Center at Clemson University.
   ``It is an excellent public awareness program about the dropout
crisis in America,'' said Dr. Jay Smink, the center's executive
director.
   ``When more parents, communities and corporations learn about
the potential we are losing, we are more likely to get them
involved in projects to keep youngsters in school,'' Smink said.
   The goal of the campaign _ to be kicked off Monday at a
Lexington news conference _ is to help reduce government statistics
showing that 682,000 students _ an average of 3,789 daily _
disappeared from their classrooms during the 1985-86 school year.
   ``The figures staggered us, and we decided to expand a program
that we've had in place about a year,'' said Dan Lacy, Ashland's
vice president for corporate communications.
   Ashland had previously launched an anti-dropout campaign in
Kentucky and West Virginia, using all media to emphasize the
importance of a high school diploma. Educators in both states
reported the campaign had an impact on youngsters who saw the
advertising.
   The idea wasn't new for Ashland, which has distributed at least
$10 million in the past five years in scholarships and college
endowments. The total does not include money spent in other fields
of education by Ashland.
   ``We approached the Advertising Council ... and asked if it
would be interested in running the program nationally, like the
ones it did on Smokey the Bear and drinking and driving,'' Lacy
said.
   There was one hitch. ``The council must have a non-profit
organization as a sponsor,'' Lacy explained.
   But Ashland found one in the Council of State Governments.
   All material that Ashland had used in its two-state drive was
donated to Doe-Anderson Advertising of Louisville for use in the
national campaign. The agency's services also were donated.
   ``Our logo was stripped from the advertisements and replaced
with that of the two councils,'' said Harry Wiley, Ashland's
director of advertising and communications.
   One of two tapes going to television stations depicts a
depressed youngster sitting in a corner of his garage. A few feet
away, an expensive sports car rests on cinder blocks.
   The narrator explains that ``two years ago, this car was the
most important thing in Joey's life. He spent every spare dime he
had on it. He even quit high school to get a job so he could have
the hottest ride in town.
   ``Today, the job is gone,'' the narrator continues. ``The car
doesn't work anymore and, without a high school diploma, neither
does Joey.
   ``Winners never quit. Stay in school,'' the ad concludes.
   The second tape depicts a teen-age mother clutching an infant.
   She tells the audience:
   ``Making ends meet hasn't been easy with three of us at home.
Jobs are pretty scarce around here, especially since neither my
husband nor me finished school.
   ``But it's going to be different for this one. He's going to
stay in high school if I have to tie him to his chair. Sometimes, I
wish someone had done me that way.''
   The tape ends with this plea: ``Stay in school. Someone's future
could depend on it.''
   Wiley estimated it will cost Ashland about $50,000 for mailing
the ads to the media. ``The packages will contain a brief summary
of how the project came about, but this is the only recognition we
will receive.''
   John Hamby, the National Dropout Prevention Center's assistant
director, said, ``There are many, many reasons why kids give up on
education. Any project that attempts to keep them from becoming a
statistic has to be a plus.''
   Hamby said studies have shown many girls cite pregnancy and
marriage as their reasons for abandoning education plans while boys
tend to blame their dislike for school.
   Both groups also mention economic reasons, Hamby said. Dropout
rates are higher among single-parent and lower-income families, he
added.
   Kentucky's dropout rate has been declining, and Ashland's
commercials, which began in August 1987, have been a factor, said
Dr. Tony Collins, director of pupil attendance in the state
Department of Education.
   In the 1983-84 school year, there were 14,224 dropouts in
Kentucky, but that number shrank to 9,633 for 1986-87.
   ``Those commercials have to get part of the credit,'' Collins
said.
   Businessmen who saw the ads came up with suggestions to help
dropouts, and Kentucky now has more residents going into the
General Education Diploma program than in past years, Collins said.
   ``And for the first time in our history, people are passing in
greater numbers than those who are quitting school,'' he said.
</TEXT>
