<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-88 1639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Iran-Oil     08-21 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Oil,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Plans to Repair Oil Facilities Hit In War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran will repair vital oil facilities
battered in the war with Iraq at ``maximum speed'' as soon as the
United Nation-sponsored cease-fire proves to be durable, Oil
Minister Golamreza Aqazadeh says.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, quoted Aqazadeh as saying Saturday Tehran will also go
ahead with major oil industry projects to boost exports, refining
capacity and exploration and expand its energy industry.
   Rebuilding its oil industry, particularly its seven existing
refineries which were badly hit, is one of Tehran's top priorities
now that the shooting has stopped.
   Aqazadeh said the Iranians want to bolster oil exports as
quickly as possible to fund the massive task of reconstruction.
   Before the cease-fire, Iran's government had projected oil
earnings of around $9 billion for this year. But weak oil prices
were expected to reduce that figure.
   Iran is currently producing around 2.3 million barrels of oil a
day, the output quota set by the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   Its current export level is an estimated 1.7 million barrels a
day, despite Iraqi efforts to choke Tehran's economic lifeline.
   Iraq's powerful air force concentrated much of its bombing
offensive on Iran's oil facilities and tankers during the
8-year-old war.
   Aqazadeh said a new oil loading terminal at Gavaneh in the
northern end of the Persian Gulf began operations soon after the
gulf war cease-fire took effect Saturday.
   Aqazadeh said the big refinery at Abadan in Khuzestan province,
put out of action early in the war, will be rebuilt and expanded
into ``one of the most sophisticated refineries of its kind.''
   The refinery, with a capacity of 630,000 barrels a day, was the
biggest in the world before it was knocked out by the Iraqis.
   The minister said another major refinery at Isfahan was now
operating at its pre-war capacity of around 200,000 barrels a day
after being bombed 15 times during the conflict.
   He did not mention the other refineries that were bombed.
Earlier this year, Western experts estimated that Iran's overall
refinery capacity of 700,000 barrels a day had been reduced by more
than one-third because of war damage.
   That forced the Iranians to import unprecedented amounts of
refined products, such as aviation fuel and kerosene, from abroad.
   Aqazadeh said Iran will push ahead with plans to build a new oil
refinery with a capacity of 220,000 barrels a day and a $1.5
billion petrochemical complex at the western city of Arak.
   The Iranians have also announced plans to build two other
smaller refineries in Tehran and the port of Taheri, midway down
the gulf near offshore oil and gas fields.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
